{{Infobox gridiron football person |name=Chip Healy |image= |birth_date={{birth date and age|1947|8|16}} |birth_place=[[Atlanta]] |death_date= |Position=[[Linebacker]] |College=[[Vanderbilt University]] |DraftedYear=1969 |DraftedRound=3 |Stats=y |DatabaseFootball= |PFR= |ProBowls= |playing_years1=1969–1970 |playing_team1=[[St. Louis Cardinals (NFL)|St. Louis Cardinals]] }}
'''Chip Healy''' is a former professional [[American football]] player who played [[linebacker]] for the [[St. Louis Cardinals (NFL)|St. Louis Cardinals]].<ref>https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/H/HealCh20.htm</ref>
After retiring from football in 1970, Healy moved around Tennessee working for his father's brokerage business, before retiring in 1987.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Healy goes from Vandy to NFL|url = http://www.vucommodores.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/091912aab.html|website = www.vucommodores.com|accessdate = 2015-12-29}}</ref> Since 2001, he has operated Transitional Living in Nashville, Tennessee, known as "Chip's Place", a treatment and living facility for men struggling with alcoholism,<ref>{{Cite web|title = About|url = http://www.chips-place.com/about.html|website = www.chips-place.com|accessdate = 2015-12-29}}</ref> which initially included Healy himself.
Healy is a devout Christian, and lives in Nashville with his dog Willie. He has two children.<ref>{{Cite web|title = article|url = http://www.chips-place.com/article.html|website = www.chips-place.com|accessdate = 2015-12-29}}</ref> His nephew, Will Healy is the head football coach at [[Austin Peay State University]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.chattanoogan.com/2015/12/22/314852/Randy-Smith-Well-Played-Young-Will.aspx|title=Randy Smith: Well Played, Young Will|access-date=2016-05-11}}</ref>
