{{Infobox climber | name = Patrick Berhault | birth_date = {{Birth date|1957|07|19|df=y}} | birth_place = [[Thiers, Puy-de-Dôme]], France | death_date = {{Death date and age|2004|04|28|1957|07|19|df=y}} | death_place = [[Dom (mountain)|Dom]] (Mischabel), Switzerland | typeofclimber = [[Free climbing|free climber]], [[mountaineer]] and [[mountain guide]] | firstascents = *'''''Pichenibule''''' (7b+) at [[Verdon Gorge]] *'''''La Haine''''' (7c+) at la Loubière/La Turbie [[Monaco]] *'''''Le Toit d'Auguste''''' (8b+) at la Loubière/La Turbie [[Monaco]] | majorascents = *'''''La grande traversée des Alpes''''', 167 days crossing the [[Alps]] from East to West (22 summits and major routes), Aug. 2000 to Feb. 2001 *'''''Award-winning 16 rock and ice link-up''''' (2003 with Philippe Magnin) in [[Mont Blanc]] *''''82 days for 82 4000m summits''''' (2004 with Philippe Magnin) in [[Alps]] | knownfor = }}
'''Patrick Berhault''' (19 July 1957 &ndash; 28 April 2004) was a professional French [[Free climbing|free climber]], [[mountaineer]] and [[mountain guide]]. He died while climbing [[Dom (mountain)|Dom]] ridge, Switzerland, during his attempt to linkup all 82 Alps 4000 meter summits in 82 days. <ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.liberation.fr/sports/0101487193-berhault-est-tombe | title=Berhault est tombé | date=2004-04-30 | publisher=[[Libération]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.ukclimbing.com/news/item.php?id=10756 | title=Patrick Berhault dies in the Alps | date=April 2004 | publisher=UKC}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.climbing.com/climber/berhault-killed-in-the-alps/ | title=Berhault Killed in the Alps | date=April 2004 | work=[[Climbing (magazine)|Climbing]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.mountain.ru/expeditions/2004/patrik_beru/index_eng.shtml | title=Patrick Berhault and Philippe Magnin - Marathon | date=2004-04-29 | publisher=Mountain.ru}}</ref>
Patrick Berhault is best known for popularizing [[sport climbing]] in France with his friend rock climber legend [[Patrick Edlinger]] in the late 70s and in the 80s. He also practiced [[free solo climbing]] and was one of the pioneer alpinists who developed light and fast mountaineering in the nineties.
